00:00:25.920 --> 00:00:30.639
So thank you all for being here, um, and sticking with me after those two amazing

00:00:30.639 --> 00:00:35.160
talks, it'll be hard to follow that up and it's quite a different topic, but I

00:00:35.160 --> 00:00:42.279
will try my best, um, and, uh, share with you how you can use, uh, Jupyter widgets

00:00:42.639 --> 00:00:44.959
to supercharge your shiny for Python.

00:00:50.119 --> 00:00:51.279
And this doesn't work either.

00:00:51.279 --> 00:00:51.599
Great.

00:00:52.599 --> 00:00:53.200
All right.

00:00:53.400 --> 00:00:57.080
Um, and when I talk about Jupyter widgets, I'm generally going to be

00:00:57.080 --> 00:01:04.199
referring to any Python code that you can execute in a Jupyter notebook cell

00:01:04.680 --> 00:01:07.599
and get a web based output results.

00:01:11.599 --> 00:01:18.239
And, uh, if you've ever written Python code before in a notebook and displayed

00:01:18.279 --> 00:01:23.279
that data, you've already used a Jupyter widget in this sense, because we're

00:01:23.279 --> 00:01:27.559
executing Python, uh, code to get a web based results.

00:01:28.199 --> 00:01:33.480
And, but that being said, you know, kind of the default, uh, rendering of

00:01:33.480 --> 00:01:36.199
a data frame is a pretty basic widget.

00:01:36.760 --> 00:01:39.720
Um, you get a limited amount of interactivity with it.

00:01:40.239 --> 00:01:43.400
Um, but they can get a whole lot more sophisticated.

00:01:44.160 --> 00:01:44.239
Yeah.

00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:50.959
So a great example of this is the quack package, which is a new Python package

00:01:51.279 --> 00:01:55.800
that makes it super easy to, you just give it a data frame and it creates a

00:01:55.800 --> 00:01:59.480
much more sophisticated interactive table.

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:04.919
And this table sort of just comes with the ability to drill down

00:02:04.919 --> 00:02:06.680
into certain values of your data.

00:02:07.160 --> 00:02:11.039
So it gives you these nice graphics at the top where you can choose certain values

00:02:11.039 --> 00:02:15.240
here, I'm choosing certain values of sex and a certain range of height.

00:02:15.800 --> 00:02:21.679
And that will drill down and just to the rows that, um, match those queries.

00:02:22.479 --> 00:02:27.080
And in addition here, notice that I also executed another code cell after

00:02:27.080 --> 00:02:32.839
interacting with the table to get the SQL attributes, uh, of this widget,

00:02:33.279 --> 00:02:37.720
which actually captures the filtered state of the data.

00:02:38.360 --> 00:02:43.639
So it's almost as if we can in Python through the Python object, access

00:02:43.639 --> 00:02:50.080
information about what the user is doing with the widget, right?

00:02:50.080 --> 00:02:55.520
So these are two really great examples that helped me kind of frame this idea

00:02:55.520 --> 00:03:00.559
that there are two broad categories of widgets when you're working in Jupyter.

00:03:01.720 --> 00:03:05.600
Um, the most broad category, which really encompasses all widgets

00:03:05.639 --> 00:03:07.440
is the idea of a one-way binding.

00:03:08.199 --> 00:03:12.360
Which really all I mean by that is that you have some Python code that you're

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:15.160
executing to get a web-based results.

00:03:15.559 --> 00:03:19.039
And any interactivity that you get from that widget, it's all

00:03:19.039 --> 00:03:21.199
happening inside of JavaScript.

00:03:21.279 --> 00:03:24.240
There's no communication back to Python.

00:03:24.520 --> 00:03:27.160
Everything is just kind of baked in and predefined.

00:03:27.479 --> 00:03:31.279
And, uh, if there's any interactivity, it's likely JavaScript.

00:03:32.279 --> 00:03:37.080
Now the two-way binding has the additional ability to send data and

00:03:37.080 --> 00:03:40.720
information back and forth between Python and JavaScript.

00:03:43.279 --> 00:03:47.759
And actually with the Jupyter widget two-way binding, they have this

00:03:47.759 --> 00:03:53.399
concept of state, both existing, both in JavaScript and Python.

00:03:54.399 --> 00:03:59.399
And, um, the framework that makes this possible, uh, will sort of

00:04:00.360 --> 00:04:04.520
automatically in some sense, detect when state changes on the front end,

00:04:04.520 --> 00:04:09.000
say in JavaScript through drilling down in our table, automatically, there will

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:14.279
be some messages sent back to Python to update the Python object with that state.

00:04:14.880 --> 00:04:19.839
And also vice versa, you can also update, uh, Python objects

00:04:19.839 --> 00:04:22.399
to then, uh, update the front end.

00:04:26.600 --> 00:04:26.880
Right.

00:04:26.880 --> 00:04:31.200
So one of the nice things about working with a one-way binding, as you

00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:34.920
can imagine with the two-way binding, there's a whole lot more complexity

00:04:34.920 --> 00:04:40.359
and overhead with, you know, passing data back and forth between Python and

00:04:40.359 --> 00:04:46.640
JavaScript, if the one-way binding kind of does the job for you, that's a great

00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:50.799
option because you can do kind of better, simpler things with it.

00:04:50.799 --> 00:04:54.200
Like, you know, not even working in notebook, you could take that Python

00:04:54.200 --> 00:04:58.600
code to create like a static webpage, maybe inside of a quarto document.

00:05:01.880 --> 00:05:06.000
But it's also kind of fundamentally more limited in this sense.

00:05:06.519 --> 00:05:12.600
Uh, mainly, you know, because we can't access any information about what's

00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:17.239
happening on the front end with our Python code, like we can't take, you

00:05:17.239 --> 00:05:22.200
know, what the user is doing to inform, um, other things in a web application.

00:05:25.160 --> 00:05:25.399
Right.

00:05:25.399 --> 00:05:32.079
So really what I mean by that, like, uh, the, the thing that makes, um, uh, this

00:05:32.079 --> 00:05:37.040
interesting from the interactivity perspective is that we can kind of access

00:05:37.040 --> 00:05:41.839
the state of what's happening on the front end and link multiple views in the

00:05:41.839 --> 00:05:45.839
sense of like they're sharing the state of what's happening to that Python object.

00:05:48.959 --> 00:05:49.200
Right.

00:05:49.200 --> 00:05:53.160
So if we go back to our interactive table with drill down capabilities,

00:05:54.279 --> 00:05:58.600
uh, you can imagine since we can actually access like what filtered data

00:05:58.600 --> 00:06:03.519
has been filtered in this table, we could take that data and route it to

00:06:03.519 --> 00:06:07.880
another view that maybe gives us like a higher dimensional picture of what's

00:06:07.880 --> 00:06:09.799
happening just in that filtered data.

00:06:15.600 --> 00:06:15.799
Right.

00:06:15.799 --> 00:06:20.799
The other big thing that the two way binding, um, gives us as a

00:06:20.799 --> 00:06:24.000
feature is this idea of mutable state.

00:06:24.399 --> 00:06:29.359
Which really means, you know, imagine you have a widget that you've just rendered

00:06:29.959 --> 00:06:37.079
and maybe you want to, um, just, uh, change a particular value of a particular

00:06:37.079 --> 00:06:41.959
attributes, which you can do is just mutate that Python objects, give it a

00:06:41.959 --> 00:06:43.920
new value for certain attributes.

00:06:44.440 --> 00:06:48.440
And just that change in states is sent to the front end.

00:06:48.440 --> 00:06:52.920
So in order to update a view, you can do it a lot more performantly by just

00:06:52.920 --> 00:07:00.040
sending only what has changed, um, from Python to JavaScript, right?

00:07:00.040 --> 00:07:04.119
So to give you a simple, concrete example of this, imagine I had a

00:07:04.119 --> 00:07:09.200
dropdown where I could choose different cities and just update the center of

00:07:09.200 --> 00:07:12.679
a map from, um, one city to the next.

00:07:13.519 --> 00:07:18.040
If I were to try to do this by re rendering the map from scratch, every

00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:22.079
time you would get a little bit of graying out and flickering every time

00:07:22.079 --> 00:07:26.559
that map updates, but by just telling the front end that only the center of

00:07:26.559 --> 00:07:32.440
the map has changed, it's able to smoothly transition from one location to the next.

00:07:37.040 --> 00:07:37.279
All right.

00:07:37.279 --> 00:07:41.559
So going back to our diagram here, there's actually like a formal name

00:07:41.559 --> 00:07:45.799
and standard and implementation of this two-way binding, which is

00:07:45.799 --> 00:07:48.160
provided by the IPyWidgets package.

00:07:49.079 --> 00:07:54.519
And you as a user might not actually end up importing from IPyWidgets.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:00.279
Uh, you may, maybe you just want to use, um, the Quack package or Plotly or Altair.

00:08:00.959 --> 00:08:05.440
Um, and all of these packages that provide this two-way binding interface

00:08:05.839 --> 00:08:11.760
are going to inherit from this widget class from IPyWidgets, because it kind

00:08:11.760 --> 00:08:15.399
of provides the foundation for passing that state back and forth

00:08:15.399 --> 00:08:17.880
between Python and JavaScript.

00:08:19.160 --> 00:08:23.440
And as we'll see shortly, the ShinyWidgets package has a render widget

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:29.519
decorator that allows us to render IPyWidgets in Shiny and leverage all of

00:08:29.519 --> 00:08:32.440
those nice things that come with the two-way binding.

00:08:36.200 --> 00:08:40.799
And most of the projects that you've heard of, um, are going to

00:08:40.840 --> 00:08:43.200
provide two-way binding interfaces.

00:08:43.200 --> 00:08:49.320
So big names like Plotly, Leaflet, Bokeh, Vega, Altair, Mapbox, um,

00:08:49.359 --> 00:08:50.640
has a binding called PyDeck.

00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:55.239
All of these projects tend to provide a two-way binding interfaces.

00:08:57.440 --> 00:09:01.919
And more than that, a lot of these big projects will also provide a

00:09:01.919 --> 00:09:06.799
one-way binding interface, which, you know, makes a whole lot of sense, uh,

00:09:06.799 --> 00:09:11.119
for the, especially from their perspective that sometimes, you know,

00:09:11.119 --> 00:09:12.840
the one-way binding does the job.

00:09:13.320 --> 00:09:17.000
Maybe you don't even want to work, uh, in a Jupyter notebook.

00:09:17.039 --> 00:09:22.320
Maybe you just want a script that, um, creates a static webpage or

00:09:22.320 --> 00:09:24.080
embedded in a Quarto document.

00:09:24.760 --> 00:09:30.159
Um, just having basically the static results with JavaScript, um, you

00:09:30.159 --> 00:09:31.640
know, requires a lot less overhead.

00:09:35.039 --> 00:09:39.000
So, um, ShinyWidgets can actually handle both of these cases.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:42.960
And what it will do is it will automatically transform a one-way binding.

00:09:42.960 --> 00:09:48.919
If you give it, if you give this one-way binding to, um, ShinyWidgets, it will

00:09:48.919 --> 00:09:52.159
automatically transform the one-way binding to a two-way binding.

00:09:53.760 --> 00:09:58.159
And this makes getting started with ShinyWidgets, um, a whole lot easier

00:09:58.200 --> 00:10:02.119
because a lot of these packages like Altair, I'm just using Altair as an

00:10:02.119 --> 00:10:06.760
example here, but this is true for like Plotly and a lot of other packages.

00:10:06.760 --> 00:10:11.000
Where the one-way binding is kind of at the heart of their

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.200
documentation and code examples.

00:10:13.239 --> 00:10:17.840
So if you actually look up Altair, you'll see Altair chart all over the place.

00:10:18.159 --> 00:10:22.359
So it's very convenient to just kind of dump those code examples

00:10:22.359 --> 00:10:24.320
into ShinyWidgets and it just works.

00:10:27.840 --> 00:10:28.159
All right.

00:10:28.159 --> 00:10:31.719
So let's get a feel for, you know, the code that you're actually going to

00:10:31.719 --> 00:10:34.200
write in order to use IPv6.

00:10:34.200 --> 00:10:38.039
The first thing you're going to want to do is start by importing ShinyWidgets.

00:10:38.760 --> 00:10:43.440
And then you can use this render widget decorator to create a rendering function.

00:10:45.440 --> 00:10:50.200
And all you need to really make sure to do in this function

00:10:50.200 --> 00:10:51.840
is to return a widget object.

00:10:55.440 --> 00:10:59.400
Now, if we were to take this kind of template and go back to our

00:10:59.960 --> 00:11:04.080
Now, if we were to take this kind of template and go back to our

00:11:04.080 --> 00:11:07.799
Quack widget that we started off with, we could start off very simple

00:11:07.799 --> 00:11:12.159
in the Shiny app by just reading in the data and making sure this

00:11:12.159 --> 00:11:16.520
rendering function returns the interactive table widget.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:20.239
Right.

00:11:20.239 --> 00:11:23.599
So we'd get a very basic result close to this.

00:11:23.640 --> 00:11:27.359
It would just be the table that you see on the top half here.

00:11:28.280 --> 00:11:33.479
But let's take that another step further and have a code chunk just

00:11:33.479 --> 00:11:38.559
below that, that will automatically update to show the SQL statement

00:11:39.080 --> 00:11:42.640
that mirrors the filtered data state.

00:11:43.239 --> 00:11:48.520
And sort of have a Shiny app that reactively updates that code cell

00:11:48.799 --> 00:11:50.919
whenever the user makes changes.

00:11:53.599 --> 00:11:53.840
Right.

00:11:53.840 --> 00:11:59.119
So let's go back to our simple Shiny app that just renders the table

00:11:59.119 --> 00:12:03.479
widget and let's add another rendering function here.

00:12:03.479 --> 00:12:08.479
I'm going to take the render code decorator from Shiny and I'm going

00:12:08.479 --> 00:12:11.239
to create another output essentially.

00:12:12.479 --> 00:12:16.880
And the first thing that this rendering function is going to want to do is

00:12:16.880 --> 00:12:22.159
gain a reference to the widget that has been rendered, and this can be a

00:12:22.159 --> 00:12:26.400
little bit awkward because there's scoping involved where you're inside

00:12:26.400 --> 00:12:30.440
of a different function, you're returning a widget object, so to make

00:12:30.440 --> 00:12:35.280
this a little bit more convenient, what the render widget decorator will

00:12:35.280 --> 00:12:40.599
do is actually attach a widget attribute where you can get at the

00:12:40.599 --> 00:12:42.479
return value of that function.

00:12:46.119 --> 00:12:46.400
Right.

00:12:46.400 --> 00:12:50.280
And if you recall to like the original notebook example that I

00:12:50.280 --> 00:12:55.559
showed at the beginning, we were executing a code cell that said

00:12:55.599 --> 00:13:03.919
essentially like w.sql to get at the SQL statement, and we can do this

00:13:03.919 --> 00:13:08.880
in a reactive sense where if we use this reactive read function to

00:13:08.880 --> 00:13:13.719
essentially read the SQL attribute, we're doing this in a reactive way

00:13:13.719 --> 00:13:18.840
that tells Shiny to say, hey, whenever this attribute changes, please

00:13:18.840 --> 00:13:23.440
invalidate the reactive context and essentially, you know, re-render

00:13:23.479 --> 00:13:25.799
the code block when SQL changes.

00:13:29.440 --> 00:13:32.919
So now we have this Shiny app that we're looking for, where now the

00:13:32.919 --> 00:13:37.880
user can come in and drill down and the SQL will update to reflect

00:13:38.119 --> 00:13:39.119
the changes in state.

00:13:44.599 --> 00:13:48.200
All right, let's take this one step further and go back to that original

00:13:48.440 --> 00:13:57.039
linked views app that I showed that has this ability to actually show

00:13:57.039 --> 00:13:59.239
you like a multidimensional picture.

00:13:59.239 --> 00:14:03.640
Here, I'm choosing a bin scatterplot of height versus weight and have

00:14:03.640 --> 00:14:08.760
that automatically update to just be showing what data that we've

00:14:08.799 --> 00:14:09.799
chosen in our tape.

00:14:09.799 --> 00:14:19.280
All right, so instead of a render code block, we're going to go back to

00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:24.559
render widgets and this time return an Altair chart instead of returning

00:14:25.280 --> 00:14:31.159
the SQL verbatim, and the start of the implementation of that render widget

00:14:31.159 --> 00:14:38.479
is very similar in the sense that we take a reactive dependency on the

00:14:38.479 --> 00:14:43.280
SQL statements behind the table to make sure that this like widget

00:14:43.280 --> 00:14:45.039
re-renders when that changes.

00:14:45.719 --> 00:14:50.159
And then feed in the filtered data to an Altair chart API and

00:14:50.159 --> 00:14:51.919
create the bin scatterplot.

00:15:01.919 --> 00:15:04.919
All right, and this point, I would just kind of like to take a step

00:15:04.919 --> 00:15:11.359
back and have us take a moment to appreciate that IPy widgets were

00:15:11.359 --> 00:15:14.599
designed for notebooks, not for Shiny.

00:15:17.359 --> 00:15:22.760
And the fact that we can even create something like Shiny widgets and,

00:15:22.960 --> 00:15:28.840
you know, leverage over a decade's worth of work in the Python community

00:15:28.840 --> 00:15:33.799
inside of Shiny for Python like this is really a matter of technical

00:15:33.799 --> 00:15:38.119
coincidence, and like there was no guarantee when we started Shiny for

00:15:38.119 --> 00:15:43.280
Python, like we were kind of scratching our heads, how are we going to, you

00:15:43.280 --> 00:15:47.479
know, allow people to use these rich interactive outputs in a way that

00:15:47.479 --> 00:15:49.440
they're kind of familiar with already?

00:15:50.280 --> 00:15:53.840
And it's kind of a miracle almost in some sense that there was two kind of

00:15:53.840 --> 00:15:57.200
parallel worlds evolving over the last decade.

00:15:57.640 --> 00:16:01.799
IPy widgets kind of came out around the same time as Shiny, like

00:16:01.799 --> 00:16:03.799
2012 or something like that.

00:16:04.440 --> 00:16:08.280
And there's been over a decade of a lot of development and work

00:16:08.320 --> 00:16:10.280
in building upon this standard.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:13.280
All right.

00:16:13.280 --> 00:16:17.479
So to give you a little bit of a picture of how we're able to kind of

00:16:17.479 --> 00:16:25.200
hook into the IPy widgets architecture, let's actually kind of take a kind of

00:16:25.239 --> 00:16:32.799
a simplified view of the architecture that's necessary to power IPy widgets.

00:16:33.679 --> 00:16:38.679
And here I have this diagram where on the left-hand side, you know, we have

00:16:38.679 --> 00:16:43.679
the Python end and on the right-hand side, we have the front end in JavaScript.

00:16:44.200 --> 00:16:51.000
And whenever you create and display a new Jupyter widget in Python, what

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:56.359
happens is the widget object sends some data and some information to what the

00:16:56.479 --> 00:17:01.520
IPy widgets developers call a com layer, which stands for communication layer,

00:17:02.119 --> 00:17:09.719
that will kind of orchestrate a message passing in a way that will power all

00:17:09.719 --> 00:17:12.319
of the widgets necessary in a notebook.

00:17:12.920 --> 00:17:17.800
So it kind of receives some data from the widget, passes that along to a front

00:17:17.800 --> 00:17:20.640
end where there's kind of a similar communication layer.

00:17:21.359 --> 00:17:26.199
And then that communication layer will then kind of know how to get to the

00:17:26.199 --> 00:17:30.400
necessary JavaScript libraries and take that data and actually

00:17:30.400 --> 00:17:32.439
render it as a interactive view.

00:17:35.959 --> 00:17:36.199
Right.

00:17:36.199 --> 00:17:42.239
So once we're rendered and the user kind of maybe comes in and interacts with the

00:17:42.239 --> 00:17:47.160
widget and introduces some changes to state, that widget view will know how to

00:17:47.160 --> 00:17:51.920
send data to the com layer to say, Hey, I have some state that has changed.

00:17:52.280 --> 00:17:58.920
Com layer passes that back all the way back to the Python object on the back end.

00:18:01.760 --> 00:18:02.000
Right.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:06.000
And one of the interesting bits here is, you know, the widget implementations

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:10.719
like Plotly, Leaflet, Altair, they're all going to be kind of responsible for

00:18:10.719 --> 00:18:15.560
this part of the stuff that happens that's very close to the actual widget

00:18:15.560 --> 00:18:17.599
object and the JavaScript view.

00:18:19.800 --> 00:18:24.760
But kind of more of the backend architecture of the com layer, this is

00:18:24.760 --> 00:18:30.479
all provided by IPyWidgets and is just kind of generically handles all

00:18:30.479 --> 00:18:32.439
different widget implementations.

00:18:34.319 --> 00:18:38.160
And it turns out these IPyWidget developers were very thoughtful about how

00:18:38.160 --> 00:18:42.119
they actually design the software for these com layers, where they've designed

00:18:42.119 --> 00:18:46.880
them to be abstract and pluggable by other environments so that you can

00:18:46.880 --> 00:18:51.239
actually kind of, they've been thoughtful about somebody like me coming in and

00:18:51.239 --> 00:18:54.239
wanting to use these widgets in another environment.

00:18:57.479 --> 00:19:01.680
And it just so happens, like that's not necessarily good enough to, you know,

00:19:02.439 --> 00:19:06.760
leverage widgets in a framework like Shiny, but it just so happens that Shiny

00:19:06.800 --> 00:19:12.800
works through message passing in a very similar way that allows us to create

00:19:12.800 --> 00:19:16.640
something like Shiny widgets and have it be interoperable with Shiny.

00:19:19.959 --> 00:19:20.160
All right.

00:19:20.160 --> 00:19:24.040
So in summary, widgets are either one-way or two-way bindings.

00:19:24.400 --> 00:19:30.280
The two-way bindings are called IPyWidgets and are much more capable.

00:19:30.280 --> 00:19:34.280
And, you know, you're able to achieve a lot more with interactivity

00:19:34.280 --> 00:19:36.040
